To perform Hierarchical Clustering based on Source Vocabulary Mapping, specifically focusing on SNOMED CT concepts that map to UMLS CUIs, you would follow these general steps:

This approach treats the SNOMED CT hierarchy (which is deeply embedded within the UMLS structure via mappings) as the basis for creating topical clusters of CUIs.

Steps for Hierarchical Clustering with SNOMED CT Mapping
1. Data Preparation: CUI to SNOMED CT Mapping
Identify Relevant CUIs: Start with the set of CUIs you are interested in analyzing.
Map to SNOMED CT: For each CUI, determine its corresponding concept(s) in SNOMED CT. A single CUI can sometimes map to multiple SNOMED CT Concept Unique Identifiers (SNOMED CT CUIs) or have alternative mappings, but you generally focus on the preferred or most frequently used map.
Extract SNOMED CT Relationships: For the identified SNOMED CT concepts, extract their structural relationships, primarily the Is a (subsumption) relationship. This forms a tree or Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG).
2. Define a Distance/Similarity Metric
Since you are using a hierarchy, you need a metric to determine how "close" two CUIs are based on their common ancestors in the SNOMED CT structure:

Common Ancestor Distance: A very common metric in concept hierarchy analysis is:
