Where:
Depth(X) is the depth of concept X in the SNOMED CT hierarchy (distance from the top-most root).
LCA(A,B) is the Lowest Common Ancestor of concepts A and B in the SNOMED CT hierarchy.
Concepts that share a very recent (deep) common ancestor are considered very similar (low distance/high similarity), forming a granular topic.
3. Apply Hierarchical Clustering
Use the calculated distance matrix from Step 2 to perform hierarchical clustering:

Agglomerative Clustering (Bottom-Up): This is the standard method for hierarchical clustering.
Start by treating every CUI as its own cluster.
Iteratively merge the two closest clusters (based on the distance metric and a chosen linkage criterion like Ward's, single, or complete linkage).
Continue until all CUIs are merged into a single, large cluster.
Dendrogram Generation: The output is a dendrogram, which visually represents the merging process.
4. Extract Granular Topics
The dendrogram allows you to cut the tree at different levels to extract topics of varying granularity:

High Granularity (Fine Topics): Cutting the dendrogram near the leaves (short vertical lines) yields many small clusters. These clusters contain CUIs that are highly specific and share a very recent common ancestor in SNOMED CT (e.g., clustering only "Fracture of left femur" and "Fracture of right femur" under a "Femur Fracture" ancestor).
Lower Granularity (Broad Topics): Cutting the dendrogram lower down yields fewer, larger clusters (e.g., a cluster for "All Fractures" or "All Injuries").
Granularity Control
The granularity of your topics is directly controlled by where you choose to "cut" the resulting dendrogram or by the linkage method and distance metric used in Step 2. A metric emphasizing the depth of the LCA will naturally lead to finer, more granular initial groupings.
